.TH httpd 3 "inets 9.6.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
httpd \- HTTP server API

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
An implementation of an HTTP 1.1 compliant web server, as defined in RFC 2616. Provides web server start options, administrative functions, and an Erlang callback API.

.SS "Data types"

.PP
Type definitions that are used more than once in this module:

.PP
\fIboolean() = true | false\fR

.PP
\fIstring/0\fR = list of ASCII characters

.PP
\fIpath() = string()\fR representing a file or a directory path

.PP
\fIip_address() = {N1,N2,N3,N4} % IPv4 | {K1,K2,K3,K4,K5,K6,K7,K8} % IPv6\fR

.PP
\fIhostname() = string()\fR representing a host, for example, "foo.bar.com"

.PP
\fIproperty() = atom()\fR

.SS "HTTP server service start & stop"

.PP
A web server can be configured to start when starting the \fIInets\fR application, or dynamically in runtime by calling the \fIInets\fR application API \fIinets:start(httpd, ServiceConfig)\fR or \fIinets:start(httpd, ServiceConfig, How)\fR, see \fIinets\fR. The configuration options, also called properties, are as follows:

.PP
\fBFile Properties\fR

.PP
When the web server is started at application start time, the properties are to be fetched from a configuration file that can consist of a regular Erlang property list, that is, \fI[{Option, Value}]\fR, where \fIOption = property() \fRand \fIValue = term()\fR, followed by a full stop. If the web server is started dynamically at runtime, a file can still be specified but also the complete property list.


