\fB\fI{log_format, common | combined}\fR\fR  Defines if access logs are to be written according to the \fIcommon\fR log format or the extended common log format. The \fIcommon\fR format is one line looking like this: \fIremotehost rfc931 authuser [date] "request" status bytes\fR.

.PP
Here:

remotehost
.RS 2
Remote.


.RE

rfc931
.RS 2
The remote username of the client (RFC 931).


.RE

authuser
.RS 2
The username used for authentication.


.RE

[date]
.RS 2
Date and time of the request (RFC 1123).


.RE

"request"
.RS 2
The request line as it came from the client (RFC 1945).


.RE

status
.RS 2
The HTTP status code returned to the client (RFC 1945).


.RE

bytes
.RS 2
The content-length of the document transferred.


.RE

.PP
The \fIcombined\fR format is one line looking like this: \fIremotehost rfc931 authuser [date] "request" status bytes "referer" "user_agent"\fR

.PP
In addition to the earlier:

"referer"
.RS 2
The URL the client was on before requesting the URL (if it could not be determined, a minus sign is placed in this field).


.RE

"user_agent"
.RS 2
The software the client claims to be using (if it could not be determined, a minus sign is placed in this field).


.RE

.PP
This affects the access logs written by \fImod_log\fR and \fImod_disk_log\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{error_log_format, pretty | compact}\fR\fR  Default is \fIpretty\fR. If the error log is meant to be read directly by a human, \fIpretty\fR is the best option.

.PP
\fIpretty\fR has a format corresponding to:

.IP
.nf
io:format("[~s] ~s, reason: ~n ~p ~n~n", [Date, Msg, Reason]).

.fi

.PP
\fIcompact\fR has a format corresponding to:

.IP
.nf
io:format("[~s] ~s, reason: ~w ~n", [Date, Msg, Reason]).

.fi

.PP
This affects the error logs written by \fImod_log\fR and \fImod_disk_log\fR.

.RE

.PP
\fBURL Aliasing Properties - Requires mod_alias\fR


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{alias, {Alias, RealName}}\fR\fR  \fIAlias = string()\fR and \fIRealName = string()\fR. \fIalias\fR allows documents to be stored in the local file system instead of the \fIdocument_root\fR location. URLs with a path beginning with url-path is mapped to local files beginning with directory-filename, for example:

.IP
.nf
{alias, {"/image", "/ftp/pub/image"}}

.fi

.PP
Access to http://your.server.org/image/foo.gif would refer to the file /ftp/pub/image/foo.gif.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{re_write, {Re, Replacement}}\fR\fR  \fIRe = string()\fR and \fIReplacement = string()\fR. \fIre_write\fR allows documents to be stored in the local file system instead of the \fIdocument_root\fR location. URLs are rewritten by \fIre:replace/3\fR to produce a path in the local file-system, for example:

.IP
.nf
{re_write, {"^/[~]([^/]+)(.*)$", "/home/\\\\1/public\\\\2"}}

.fi

.PP
Access to http://your.server.org/~bob/foo.gif would refer to the file /home/bob/public/foo.gif.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{directory_index, [string()]}\fR\fR  \fIdirectory_index\fR specifies a list of resources to look for if a client requests a directory using a \fI/\fR at the end of the directory name. \fIfile\fR depicts the name of a file in the directory. Several files can be given, in which case the server returns the first it finds, for example:

.IP
.nf
{directory_index, ["index.html", "welcome.html"]}

.fi

.PP
Access to http://your.server.org/docs/ would return http://your.server.org/docs/index.html or http://your.server.org/docs/welcome.html if index.html does not exist.

.RE

